Early voting is now open through November 1st! I would be honored to have your vote to continue representing portions of Walton, Morgan, Newton & Henry counties at the Georgia State Senate. I am ready to continue the mission to fight inflation and lower taxes, address the effects of illegal immigration, offer support for at-risk children, and reform mental health care. 

If we haven't met yet, I'd love to introduce myself. I married the love of my life, Lindsay, in 2014 and we are raising our two boys, Charles Willis and Beecher, in my hometown of McDonough. I was first elected to the State House in 2012, and I served in the House until I ran for State Senate in 2017. I have served in the Senate since January of 2018 and currently serve as the Chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee. I am a partner at Smith, Welch, Webb, and White and manage a general litigation law practice. Frank Russo, Director of the CPAC Foundation‚Äôs Center for Combating Human Trafficking, recently shared testimony with Ranking Member Senator Chuck Grassley of the Budget Committee on the crisis involving unaccompanied minors in America. Our testimony raised awareness about the systemic failures within the Office of Refugee Resettlement (ORR) and the devastating impact these shortcomings have on vulnerable children. 

Specifically, we brought attention to the significant shortcomings of the current administration's border policies, which have inadvertently facilitated the trafficking of thousands of children across state lines. With approximately 370,000 unaccompanied alien children crossing the southern border under the Biden administration, and studies indicating that 60% of these children fall into the hands of cartels, it is imperative to address the lack of adequate oversight and enforcement. The misuse of government benefits by traffickers and the ORR's inadequate vetting of guardians further exacerbate the crisis.

We are grateful for the opportunity to collaborate with Senator Grassley and other members of Congress committed to combating human trafficking. The submission of this testimony is a testament to our unwavering dedication to protecting the most vulnerable among us and our resolve to drive meaningful change. We believe that with increased awareness and legislative support, we can make significant strides in ending child trafficking and holding those who exploit our immigration system accountable. This testimony is not just a call to action; it is a call to uphold the values of justice, safety, and dignity for all children. You can read our full submission at CPAC.org/Blog.

President Donald J. Trump delivered remarks at CPAC 2018 highlighting the accomplishments of his administration in just the first year of this term.

Trump‚Äôs deregulation initiatives especially won the support of farmers and home builders for freeing up their lives, restoring their dignity, and allowing their businesses to grow. Reopening the energy industry promoted remarkable nationwide growth and allowed the United States to compete on the world stage, to the detriment of our enemies. 

While delivering economic blows to our foreign foes in China, Russia, and Iran, Trump also improved relations with our allies. I am a legal immigrant from Latin America and I am fighting hard to prevent the same destructive socialist policies which damaged our neighbors in South America from coming to the United States.

We must not allow the Democrats to defund the police. We must support our veterans and give them more, better choices in healthcare services. We must embrace school choice from the federal level and encourage competition in curricula. We must balance our budget and focus on reducing inflation by reducing government spending and printing. We must secure our border and introduce immigration reform that fits the modern era. We must reduce foreign influence on and acquisition of US single family housing and agricultural land. We must uphold free speech and ensure that every American has the right to share their opinions on public platforms.

I STRONGLY SUPPORT OUR ARMENIAN NEIGHBORS

Armenian voters in California's 32nd Congressional District often care about a mix of issues tied to their cultural heritage, community needs, and broader political concerns. I support their priorities, which include:

1. **Recognition of the Armenian Genocide**: This is a deeply important issue for many Armenian-Americans, and I advocate for genocide recognition and historical injustices.

2. **Support for Armenia and Artsakh (Nagorno-Karabakh)**: Given the complex geopolitics of the South Caucasus, Armenians often look for us to support U.S. foreign aid to Armenia and Artsakh, as well as those who speak out on regional security, especially in the context of conflict with Azerbaijan. I do support.

3. **Immigration and Family Reunification**: Many Armenian families have members abroad, so immigration policies that support family reunification and streamline the legal immigration process are of great interest to them. I support.

4. **Economic and Social Issues**: Like other neighbors, Armenian-Americans are concerned with local and national issues such as healthcare, education, affordable housing, and economic opportunities, especially in districts like California‚Äôs 32nd, which includes diverse communities. I am also concerned.

5. **Diaspora and Cultural Preservation**: I promote policies that help preserve the Armenian language, culture, and community institutions in the U.S.

6. **Legislation**:  I also endorse Adam Schiff's H.R.96666, which requires the President of the United States to seize Azerbaijani assets and create a process for Armenians displaced from Artsakh to claim such assets as compensation for lost revenue, and for other purposes.

I also like Armenian food, especially the Lamb Chops at Restaurant Areni here in our District CA-32. The service is excellent.

Dear Neighbors:

In my long ago youth I had the honor and privilege to play football at the University of Georgia. The teams I played on were not as good as the Dawgs of today, but we were led by a Hall of Fame coach named Vince Dooley. That's me in the picture on the right (#56) helping carry Coach Dooley off the field in his last game (we beat Michigan State on January 1, 1989 in the Gator Bowl to finish the year ranked #15 at 9-3).

That was also my last competitive football game, but a lot of the lessons I learned still shape my life today. Also the memories I shared with my teammates are things I cherish, like the relationship I had with Bryant Gantt, who was hurt that game but is still carrying coach off the field (Bryant now works at UGA and you usually see him on the sideline when the Red and Black play on TV). In our house, we had a bit of a trip down memory lane a week ago on Gallatin High's "College Gameday" which was part of homecoming week - both of our kids decided to "represent" the Bulldogs. Was a bit of a proud moment for me because I usually get eyerolling from our teenagers for talking about the "dinosaur days".

Coach Dooley always taught us that "a commitment is a commitment", and when you give your word to someone you keep it. After marrying a Montana girl and proudly calling the Gallatin Valley our home for more than a decade, I know that maxim rings true here as well. So I'd like to share my commitment to the people in HD 63:

¬∑    I firmly believe in the traditional Republican values of limited and small government. We need to find ways to reduce spending thus easing the tax burden crushing Montana families.

¬∑    While many people, especially those in the media, get lost in memes of people in Ohio eating cats or dogs or gees, frankly I think that conversation is missing the point. Unchecked immigration is causing significant problems in this country (and other countries as well). The words written on the Statue of Liberty: "Give me your tired, your poor, Your huddled masses yearning to breathe free, The wretched refuse of your teeming shore. Send these, the homeless, tempest-tossed to me, I lift my lamp beside the golden door!" embody an ideal worth preserving, but not at the expense of the rule of law. I believe we need not only to enforce the immigration laws in place, but also to work on reforming the immigration situation. It's a big issue, and Montanans should not have to bear the financial burden of people living in this country illegally.

¬∑    Medicare expansion is a huge issue for the next legislative session, maybe the most important one of the upcoming session. Almost 100,000 Montanans rely on this program. We need to find a way to continue this program for those most at risk, and I will work hard to be part of the solution.

¬∑    I do not believe the last election was stolen. It was a tough race, and Joe Biden was fairly elected as president. I want both of the current candidates to do a better job telling us what they will do instead of what the other candidate won't do. But, I do think that a person should have to validate or prove their citizenship before being allowed to register to vote - that's the law and it there should be safeguards to ensure it's enforced.

¬∑    I believe that hatred, bigotry and division have no place in politics or governing. As it says in our pledge, we are "one nation under God, indivisible, with liberty and justice for all". To me those are not just words, they are ideals. If elected I would work to make sure those values are reflected in our laws and how we govern.

¬∑    I believe that the right to choose should be protected for women. That right exists in Montana's constitution, and it must remain protected. That doesn't mean I want people to have abortions. However, I believe that decision should be made by the woman who is pregnant.

I believe that I'm the best candidate for HD 63. I care about this community. I live in this district. Our kids go to school in this district. I'm asking for your vote to represent you and your family, guided by these commonsense principles I've laid out. If you agree with some, most or even all of my views I'd appreciate your support.

Please send me questions that matter to you. My e-mail is markalewis56@gmail.com. My cell phone is 406.599.3243.

ad_creative_bodies:
Victor Harris and Skyla Edwards are committed to securing Arizona‚Äôs border and protecting our communities from the dangers posed by illegal immigration, human trafficking, and drug smuggling. üöß

Arizona‚Äôs proximity to the southern border makes us a frontline state in the fight against these threats, and we must take decisive action to ensure the safety of our families and our state.

Here‚Äôs what Vic and Skyla will do:

- Stop the flow of illegal drugs, including fentanyl, by increasing law enforcement resources and working with federal agencies to intercept dangerous substances before they reach our streets.
- Combat human trafficking, which has become a serious issue, particularly affecting women and children. We‚Äôll ensure law enforcement has the tools they need to disrupt trafficking networks and support victims in rebuilding their lives.
- Reinforce border security by investing in modern technology, physical barriers where necessary, and additional personnel to keep our border safe.
- Enforce our immigration laws fairly and strongly, ensuring that those who enter our country do so legally and responsibly, while protecting the rights of legal immigrants.
- Protect Arizona‚Äôs resources by ensuring taxpayer dollars are spent wisely, prioritizing Arizona citizens and legal residents.

LD26 is struggling with crime, poverty, and drugs‚Äîand securing the border is a crucial step in addressing these issues head-on. Vic and Skyla are fighting for a stronger, safer Arizona.

üó≥Ô∏è Vote for Victor Harris for State Senate and Skyla Edwards for State House on or before November 5th. Together, we will secure our border and protect our communities.

Find your voting location at https://locations.maricopa.vote and learn more at https://skyla.vote/border/

Senator Tim Nangle's failed leadership and reckless far-left policy decisions on critical issues are having a detrimental impact on the lives of Maine's residents. His inability to effectively address the state's pressing concerns has led to negative consequences, undermining the well-being of the community and compromising Maine's future prosperity.
Learn More: www.windhamgop.com/windham-s-failed-leadership

- **Opposition to Senior Property Tax Relief**: Nangle opposed measures aimed at providing property tax relief for seniors. This position has been criticized for neglecting the financial needs of elderly residents who are struggling with increased living costs, highlighting a lack of leadership in addressing the concerns of vulnerable populations ([Maine Legislature Records](https://legislature.maine.gov/records/senate-record), [Maine Public](https://www.mainepublic.org/politics/2023-07-03/lawmakers-to-vote-on-900m-spending-bill-that-replaces-senior-tax-freeze-program)).

- **Support for Lenient Immigration Policies**: Nangle has supported far-left policies that provide access to a wide variety of state services for undocumented immigrants, reflecting a lenient approach that incentivizes illegal immigration. This policy stance has been viewed as reckless and as a failure to prioritize public resources for legal residents ([Maine Legislature Bill Information](https://legislature.maine.gov/legis/bills)). 

- **Promotion of Costly Green Energy Initiatives**: Nangle has championed green energy initiatives that place a significant financial burden on taxpayers while disproportionately benefiting select industries. His extreme far-left approach has been labeled as economically reckless, with inadequate consideration of the broader impact on Maine residents' energy costs and financial stability ([Maine Legislature Green Energy Votes](https://legislature.maine.gov/legis/bills), [Maine Public](www.mainepublic.org/politics/2023-07-07/after-intense-debate-and-lobbying-lawmakers-approve-tweaks-to-solar-subsidies)).

- **Support for Gender-Affirming Care for Minors**: Senator Nangle endorsed bills which mandate that MaineCare provide coverage for gender-affirming care, including treatments for gender dysphoria. This promotes irreversible medical procedures for minors without adequate safeguards, reflecting a reckless approach to sensitive healthcare issues ([Maine Legislature PDF](https://legislature.maine.gov/legis/bills/getPDF.asp?paper=HP0676&item=1&snum=131)).

- **Backing Full-Term Abortion Policies**: Nangle has supported legislation that allows abortions up to the point of birth, removes the criminal penalties for performing an abortion without being licensed as a medical professional, and for performing an abortion after viability of the fetus when it is not necessary for the preservation of the life or health of the mother. This stance has been criticized for undermining protections for unborn children, showcasing failed leadership on critical ethical issues ([Maine Legislature Statutes](https://legislature.maine.gov/statutes/22/title22sec1598.html), [Title 22, ¬ß1598: Abortions](https://legislature.maine.gov/statutes/22/title22sec1598.html), [131st Maine Legislature](getPDF.asp (maine.gov)).
